Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Wave-5 cirrus5 capture (/tmp/cirrus5/SDLDBG.LOG lines 38-79) confirmed
two facts that, taken together, kill the LFB-on-Cirrus story:

  1. Patch 0018's display-start GET reports X=0 Y=0 (offset=0):
        display-start GET (pre-set):  X=0 Y=0 (offset=0) ax=0x004F
        display-start SET attempt:    X=0 Y=0 ax=0x004F
        display-start GET (post-set): X=0 Y=0 (offset=0) ax=0x004F

     so writes to LFB offset 0 SHOULD be visible — but...

  2. The Loading splash stuck on screen for the entire run; 100+
     post-flush DOSVESA-FB-CALLs hit LFB at vram_phys=0x78000000 and
     none of them appeared on the visible display.

Conclusion: on Cirrus CL-GD5434 + UNIVBE 6.7, the LFB aperture
(0x78000000) and the displayed VRAM region are decoupled. Writes to
the aperture update VRAM cells the display generator does not read
from. No VBE-side fix is reachable; this is below the BIOS interface.

Wave-1's BANKED path on the same Cirrus card showed visible "Loading
+ partial title scene" updates — so the banked window at A000:0
remains the working route on this hardware.

Fix C: auto-disable LFB on cards matching the Cirrus + UNIVBE
fingerprint, and add a manual hint as escape hatch.

Implementation
--------------

Two activation paths:

  a. Auto-detection. DOSVESA_DetectLFBApertureBug (new public helper
     in SDL_dosmodes.[ch]) reads the cached VESA controller info and
     fingerprints against:

       - Exact: vendor "SciTech Software, Inc." + product containing
         "Display Doctor" + total VRAM 1024 KB. Matches the cirrus5
         capture exactly. UNIVBE rewrites OEM strings so the chip
         identity is hidden behind UNIVBE; VRAM size is the proxy
         for "this is a Cirrus 1MB card running UNIVBE."

       - Loose: "Cirrus" or "CL-GD" anywhere in any OEM string.
         Catches native Cirrus VBE without UNIVBE (uncommon).

     Logs `cirrus-lfb-aperture-bug: detected (oem=... product=...
     vram=...KB) -> forcing banked path (reason: ...)` on match,
     `cirrus-lfb-aperture-bug: NOT detected ...` otherwise. Either
     way the result lands in SDLDBG.LOG so the detection outcome is
     always traceable.

     DOSVESA_VideoInit calls this once at init and stores the result
     in SDL_VideoData::force_banked_path (new field).

  b. Manual hint. SDL_HINT_DOS_DISABLE_LFB=1 forces the banked path
     regardless of detection. Useful for diagnostics or for cards
     exhibiting the same bug we haven't fingerprinted yet. Read at
     each populate_fb_state_for_direct_fb call (cheap, no caching).

populate_fb_state_for_direct_fb (SDL_dosframebuffer.c) ORs the auto-
detect bit and the hint into a single `force_banked` decision; when
true and banked is usable, the helper takes the banked dosmemput path
even when LFB would otherwise win the prefer_lfb / use_lfb_path
calculation. One log line fires when the override actually changes
the path:

    [lifecycle] DISABLE_LFB engaged: auto=N hint=N -> banked path
    (would have used LFB otherwise: prefer_lfb=N banked_usable=1)

Verified under DOSBox-X parity smoke (build/stage/SDLDBG.LOG):

  - No SDL_DOS_DISABLE_LFB env: detection runs, no fingerprint match
    on DOSBox-X's S3 Trio64 emulation (vendor='DOSBox Development
    Team' product='DOSBox - The DOS Emulator' vram=2048KB), LFB path
    remains enabled. Title scene renders correctly through LFB.

  - With SDL_DOS_DISABLE_LFB=1: same detection result, but the hint
    forces banked anyway. CreateWindowFramebuffer reports
    use_dosmemput=1 vram_phys=0x000a0000 (banked window), and the
    title + post-Z intro scene renders correctly through the banked
    dosmemput path.

The hint mechanism is also the safe deploy path for Cirrus real-HW
gateways where the manual override sidesteps any fingerprint-miss
risk on cards with subtly different OEM strings.

Why DOS needs this
------------------

The aperture-vs-display VRAM decoupling on Cirrus + UNIVBE is a real
hardware/firmware constraint that VBE 0x4F07 doesn't expose and we
cannot work around at the LFB layer. Auto-disabling LFB on
fingerprint-matched cards keeps the banked path available where it
works, while leaving LFB enabled on Mach64 / M64VBE (the gateway /
PODP-machine target) where banked is bandwidth-bound and LFB is
5-10× faster.

Local-only patch per workspace policy (memory note "SDL upstream —
local patches only"): never PR'd upstream.

